In this article, a senior administration official discusses the main points of President Obama's commencement address at West Point. The President focused on defining the next phase of US foreign policy, particularly in relation to counterterrorism and US leadership in the world. The official highlights the decision to wind down the war in Afghanistan and the need to build a network of partners in the region to deal with the terrorist threat. The President also announced plans to establish a Counterterrorism Partnerships Fund of up to $5 billion to provide funding and resources for capacity building. The official also discusses the administration's support for the Syrian opposition and the possibility of increased military assistance, as well as the importance of addressing climate change and the need for China to adhere to international rules and norms. The official also mentions the administration's intention to review the Authorization for Use of Military Force (AUMF) and close the Guantanamo Bay detention facility.